2026-06-23 | Count ZigZag Arrays

	Question
Return the number of valid arrays modulo 10^9+7.
	Key Insight
For a new element, validity depends only on the previous two elements.
If we know:
		prev2 = a
		prev1 = b
then while choosing c:
		b != c
and
		not(a < b < c)
and
		not(a > b > c)
So a DP on the last two values naturally appears.
	State Definition
		dp[a][b]
	= number of valid arrays ending with
		..., a, b
	where a ≠ b.
	Transition
	Try every possible c in [l,r]:
		b != c
		and
		not(a < b < c)
		and
		not(a > b > c)
	then:
		dp[b][c] += dp[a][b]
	Base Case
	Length 1:
		all values are valid.
	Length 2:
		any pair of distinct values is valid.
	Answer:
		sum of all states after length n.
	Naive Complexity
		O(n * m³)
	where
		m = r-l+1
	This is too slow if m is large.
	Optimization
	Observe:
		a < b
	implies
		c ≤ b
	because
		a < b < c
	is forbidden.
	Similarly:
		a > b
	implies
		c ≥ b
	because
		a > b > c
	is forbidden.
	So only the relation between the last two values matters.
	State Compression
		UP   : previous pair increasing
		DOWN : previous pair decreasing
	Let values be compressed into:
		1...m
	Define:
		up[x]
		=
		arrays ending at value x
		where previous step was increasing
		down[x]
		=
		arrays ending at value x
		where previous step was decreasing
	Using prefix sums we can transition in O(m).
	Final Complexity
		O(n * m)
	where
		m = r-l+1
	Time Complexity
		O(n * (r-l+1))
	Space Complexity
		O(r-l+1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    static constexpr int MOD = 1000000007;

    int zigZagArrays(int n, int l, int r) {

        int m = r - l + 1;

        if (n == 1)
            return m;

        vector<long long> dp(m);

        // length = 2
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++)
            dp[i] = i;

        for (int len = 3; len <= n; len++) {

            vector<long long> ndp(m);

            long long pref = 0;

            for (int x = 0; x < m; x++) {
                ndp[x] = pref;
                pref = (pref + dp[m - 1 - x]) % MOD;
            }

            dp.swap(ndp);
        }

        long long ans = 0;

        for (int x = 0; x < m; x++) {
            ans = (ans + dp[x]) % MOD;
        }

        ans = (2 * ans) % MOD;

        return (int)ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
	The condition "no three consecutive numbers are strictly increasing or strictly decreasing" means the direction between consecutive elements must alternate. Therefore, instead of remembering the last two values explicitly, we only need to remember whether the last movement was UP or DOWN and the current value. This reduces the problem from a cubic DP to an O(n · (r−l+1)) dynamic programming solution.
